Note: HIR to Dockerfile Backend - Converts HIR directly to Dockerfile source text
Note: Part of Translation universal language translation system
Note: Walks HIR function-call statements that lower from Dockerfile instructions and
Note: emits canonical Dockerfile text via the shared emitter_common byte buffer.
Note: This is the architectural reverse of dockerfile_to_hir.runa: HIR in, text out,
Note: NO frontend AST construction. Mirrors the hir_to_json / hir_to_yaml /
Note: hir_to_toml backend shape.

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/emitter_common.runa" as EmitterCommon

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Form discriminants
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
SHELL_FORM and EXEC_FORM are the two surface variants for RUN, CMD,
ENTRYPOINT and HEALTHCHECK CMD instructions in Dockerfile grammar. The
lowering side (dockerfile_to_hir.runa) stores these as the int64 payload
of a HIR_LITERAL passed through HEALTHCHECK CMD's "form" argument. The
values match the canonical constants in dockerfile_parser.runa
(SHELL_FORM=2000, EXEC_FORM=2001) so any future lowering change must
update both sides. They are defined locally here rather than imported to
keep this backend completely independent of the frontend parser module.
@End Reasoning

Constant SHELL_FORM as Integer is 2000
Constant EXEC_FORM as Integer is 2001

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Translation Strategy
Note: ============================================================================

Note: HIR function calls lowered from Dockerfile instructions are translated
Note: directly to Dockerfile source bytes. There is no intermediate frontend AST.
Note: Each dockerfile_* function corresponds to one Dockerfile instruction line.

Note: Example forward translations:
Note:   call dockerfile_from("ubuntu", "20.04", "", "builder", "")
Note:   → FROM ubuntu:20.04 AS builder

Note:   call dockerfile_run_shell("apt-get update")
Note:   → RUN apt-get update

Note:   call dockerfile_copy(["/app"], "/dest", "builder", "", "", false)
Note:   → COPY --from=builder /app /dest

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Backend State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Backend state owns a raw byte emitter (the destination buffer for Dockerfile
source) plus a latched error channel. Unlike the previous AST-building
implementation, no node-pool or AST-root pointer is needed — the emitter
buffer IS the output.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three int64 fields packed at offsets 0 (emitter pointer), 8 (error_message
String), 16 (has_error flag). 24 bytes total. The emitter is created in
create_backend and destroyed in free_backend; the caller takes ownership of
the materialised string via emitter_raw_get_output before destruction.
@End Implementation

Type called "HIRToDockerfileBackend":
    emitter as Integer
    error_message as String
    has_error as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Backend Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Two-stage allocation: 24-byte backend record, then a raw byte emitter that
will accumulate every byte of the resulting Dockerfile. Allocation failure
of the emitter aborts construction so callers never see a partially-built
backend whose emitter slot is null.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates the backend struct, then calls emitter_raw_create. On emitter
allocation failure the backend struct is freed and 0 is returned.
Zero-initialises error_message to the empty string and has_error to 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_backend" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a new HIR→Dockerfile backend with an attached raw byte emitter.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate backend record (24 bytes), attach a raw byte emitter,
    initialize error fields to the empty / zero defaults.
    @End Implementation

    Let backend_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 24

    If backend_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let emitter_ptr be proc emitter_raw_create from EmitterCommon

    If emitter_ptr is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with backend_ptr
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with backend_ptr, 0, emitter_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with backend_ptr, 8, ""
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with backend_ptr, 16, 0

    Return backend_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Symmetric counterpart to create_backend. Releases the emitter buffer first
(it holds the only owned heap pointer outside the struct) then deallocates
the backend struct itself. Null-tolerant so callers may invoke it
unconditionally in cleanup paths.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the emitter pointer at offset 0, destroys the emitter via
emitter_raw_destroy if non-zero, then deallocates the backend record.
@End Implementation

Process called "free_backend" that takes backend_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Free the backend record and its attached emitter.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Destroy the emitter first, then release the struct.
    @End Implementation

    If backend_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let emitter_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with backend_ptr, 0

    If emitter_ptr is not equal to 0:
        proc emitter_raw_destroy from EmitterCommon with emitter_ptr
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with backend_ptr
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Error recording is latched: the most recent message wins and has_error
becomes 1. Callers poll has_error after translate_* invocations to
short-circuit when input is malformed. Multiple overwrites are intentional
(last error in chain is most actionable).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Writes message to offset 8 and 1 to offset 16. No allocation: the String
pointer is stored directly so the caller must keep the message live for
the lifetime of the backend (or until the next set_backend_error call).
@End Implementation

Process called "set_backend_error" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, message as String returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Record a backend error message and set the error flag.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Store the message at offset 8 and set has_error at offset 16.
    @End Implementation

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with backend_ptr, 8, message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with backend_ptr, 16, 1
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Local integer formatter
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The Dockerfile backend needs to format EXPOSE port numbers and HEALTHCHECK
retries as decimal text. The bootstrap stdlib integer formatter is not in
this module's import graph, so a minimal local converter is shipped. Same
shape as the one in hir_to_json.runa.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Special-cases zero with a two-byte "0\0" allocation. For non-zero values
records the sign, takes the absolute value, counts decimal digits with a
divide loop, allocates length+1 bytes, then writes digits right-to-left
using modulo 10. Inserts '-' at index 0 if input was negative and
null-terminates.
@End Implementation

Process called "format_integer" that takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Convert an integer to a freshly allocated decimal C-string.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Right-to-left digit emission into an exactly-sized buffer.
    @End Implementation

    If value is equal to 0:
        Let zero_result be proc allocate from Layout with 2
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with zero_result, 0, 48
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with zero_result, 1, 0
        Return zero_result
    End If

    Let is_negative be 0
    Let abs_value be value

    If value is less than 0:
        Set is_negative to 1
        Set abs_value to 0 minus value
    End If

    Let digit_count be 0
    Let remaining be abs_value

    While remaining is greater than 0:
        Set digit_count to digit_count plus 1
        Set remaining to remaining divided by 10
    End While

    Let str_length be digit_count

    If is_negative is equal to 1:
        Set str_length to str_length plus 1
    End If

    Let result be proc allocate from Layout with str_length plus 1

    If result is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let index be str_length minus 1
    Set remaining to abs_value

    While remaining is greater than 0:
        Let digit be remaining modulo by 10
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with result, index, 48 plus digit
        Set remaining to remaining divided by 10
        Set index to index minus 1
    End While

    If is_negative is equal to 1:
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with result, 0, 45
    End If

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with result, str_length, 0

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR Accessor Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Defensive String extractor for HIR_LITERAL nodes. Returns the empty string
for both a null pointer and a node of an unexpected type because the
caller (translate_*_call) uses the empty string as its sentinel for
"argument absent / unrepresentable" and would otherwise dereference garbage.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
HIR node layout begins with the type tag at offset 0; HIR_LITERAL stores
its string payload at offset 40. Both offsets must match hir.runa or the
translator will silently produce wrong Dockerfile output.
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_string_literal" that takes hir_node_ptr as Integer returns String:
    @Reasoning
    Extract a String value from a HIR_LITERAL node, "" on any malformed input.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Type-tag check at offset 0, then read string payload at offset 40.
    @End Implementation

    If hir_node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_node_ptr, 0

    If node_type is equal to HIR_LITERAL from HIR:
        Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_node_ptr, 40
        Return value
    End If

    Return ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Integer counterpart to extract_string_literal. 0 is the safe sentinel for
malformed input because EXPOSE / STOPSIGNAL / similar fields treat 0 as
"not specified" downstream.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the int64 payload at offset 40 of a HIR_LITERAL node — same offset
as the string extractor because HIR_LITERAL aliases its payload field by
node subtype rather than by separate storage.
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_integer_literal" that takes hir_node_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Extract an Integer value from a HIR_LITERAL node, 0 on any malformed input.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Type-tag check at offset 0, then read int64 payload at offset 40.
    @End Implementation

    If hir_node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_node_ptr, 0

    If node_type is equal to HIR_LITERAL from HIR:
        Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_node_ptr, 40
        Return value
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Booleans are stored in HIR as int64 with value 0 or 1. This helper exists
distinct from extract_integer_literal solely so the COPY/ADD link-flag
call sites read as documentation of intent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Same payload as extract_integer_literal at offset 40 of HIR_LITERAL.
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_boolean_literal" that takes hir_node_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Extract a Boolean (0/1) from a HIR_LITERAL node.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read int64 payload at offset 40.
    @End Implementation

    If hir_node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_node_ptr, 0

    If node_type is equal to HIR_LITERAL from HIR:
        Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_node_ptr, 40
        Return value
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR_ARRAY_LITERAL stores its elements as a List of child HIR nodes. The
elements_ptr field at offset 24 holds the raw List handle. Callers iterate
that List and apply per-element extractors (string, integer, tuple) as
appropriate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Type-tag check then read offset 24 (children list).
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_array_children" that takes hir_array_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return the List handle of a HIR_ARRAY_LITERAL's children, 0 on bad input.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Type-tag check at offset 0, read child list pointer at offset 24.
    @End Implementation

    If hir_array_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_array_ptr, 0

    If node_type is not equal to HIR_ARRAY_LITERAL from HIR:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let elements_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_array_ptr, 24
    Return elements_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR_TUPLE_LITERAL stores its element nodes as a child List at offset 24.
Tuples encode positional pairs (e.g., LABEL key/value, EXPOSE port/protocol)
where the caller already knows the arity. Elements stay raw HIR nodes —
the caller invokes the appropriate literal extractor on each based on
position.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Type-tag check then read offset 24.
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_tuple_children" that takes hir_tuple_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return the List handle of a HIR_TUPLE_LITERAL's children, 0 on bad input.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Type-tag check at offset 0, read child list pointer at offset 24.
    @End Implementation

    If hir_tuple_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_tuple_ptr, 0

    If node_type is not equal to HIR_TUPLE_LITERAL from HIR:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let elements_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_tuple_ptr, 24
    Return elements_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
The dispatcher in translate_hir_call needs the callee identifier to pick the
correct translate_*_call handler. HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION stores its callee as
a child HIR_IDENTIFIER node at offset 24, not as an inline string, so this
helper walks that one hop while returning "" if the callee is computed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read callee_ptr at offset 24, check its type tag is HIR_IDENTIFIER, then
read its name string at offset 40.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_function_name" that takes hir_call_ptr as Integer returns String:
    @Reasoning
    Extract the function name from a HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION's callee identifier.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Walk callee pointer at offset 24 and read identifier name at offset 40.
    @End Implementation

    If hir_call_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_call_ptr, 0

    If node_type is not equal to HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION from HIR:
        Return ""
    End If

    Let callee_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_call_ptr, 24

    If callee_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Let callee_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_ptr, 0

    If callee_type is equal to HIR_IDENTIFIER from HIR:
        Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_ptr, 40
        Return name
    End If

    Return ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION stores its argument list pointer at offset 32 (offset
24 is the callee). Centralising this access here means a future schema
change only edits one place rather than every translate_*_call site.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Type-tag check at offset 0, read arguments list pointer at offset 32.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_call_arguments" that takes hir_call_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return the List handle of a HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION's arguments, 0 on bad input.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Type-tag check at offset 0, read args list pointer at offset 32.
    @End Implementation

    If hir_call_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_call_ptr, 0

    If node_type is not equal to HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION from HIR:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let args_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with hir_call_ptr, 32
    Return args_ptr
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Low-level emit helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single-call shorthand for appending a C-string to the backend's raw byte
emitter. Used by every translate_*_call so the implementation reads as
plain "emit string X" rather than threading the emitter handle through
every line.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the emitter pointer from offset 0 of the backend, calls
emitter_raw_emit_string.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_text" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, text as String returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Append text to the backend's raw byte emitter.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Forwards to emitter_raw_emit_string after extracting the emitter handle.
    @End Implementation

    Let emitter_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with backend_ptr, 0
    proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter_ptr, text
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Newline (LF) byte. Dockerfile uses Unix line endings universally. Each
instruction emitter ends with one of these so consecutive instructions
sit on their own lines.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emit byte 10 through the raw emitter.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_newline_byte" that takes backend_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Append a single LF byte to the buffer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Forwards to emitter_raw_emit_byte with code point 10.
    @End Implementation

    Let emitter_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with backend_ptr, 0
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter_ptr, 10
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
JSON array emission for Dockerfile exec-form instructions (RUN, CMD,
ENTRYPOINT, VOLUME with multiple paths, SHELL, HEALTHCHECK CMD exec).
Renders each element as a double-quoted string, comma-space separated,
enclosed in square brackets. Matches the dockerfile_printer.runa output
form precisely so round-trips are byte-identical.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emit "[", loop the args list emitting `"arg"` for each element with ", "
between, emit "]". Each element is read from the List via list_get.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_json_array_from_strings" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, strings_list as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emit a JSON-style array of double-quoted strings.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Bracket-delimited, comma-space separated, double-quoted strings.
    @End Implementation

    proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "["

    If strings_list is equal to 0:
        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "]"
        Return 1
    End If

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with strings_list

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arg_count:
        If i is greater than 0:
            proc emit_text with backend_ptr, ", "
        End If

        Let element be proc list_get from List with strings_list, i
        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "\""
        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, element
        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "\""

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "]"
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Variant of emit_json_array_from_strings that consumes a List of HIR_LITERAL
nodes (as found inside a HIR_ARRAY_LITERAL's children list). Calls
extract_string_literal on each element so the same emission convention
applies whether the source is raw strings or HIR nodes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Bracket-delimited, comma-space separated, double-quoted strings, with each
element resolved through extract_string_literal.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_json_array_from_hir" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, hir_nodes_list as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emit a JSON-style array of strings extracted from HIR literal nodes.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Bracket-delimited, comma-space separated, double-quoted extracted strings.
    @End Implementation

    proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "["

    If hir_nodes_list is equal to 0:
        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "]"
        Return 1
    End If

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with hir_nodes_list

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than arg_count:
        If i is greater than 0:
            proc emit_text with backend_ptr, ", "
        End If

        Let element_node be proc list_get from List with hir_nodes_list, i
        Let element_str be proc extract_string_literal with element_node

        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "\""
        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, element_str
        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "\""

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "]"
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Per-instruction translators (HIR call → Dockerfile text)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
FROM lowers from dockerfile_from(image, tag, digest, stage_name, platform).
Strict arity 5 — the lowering is canonical so missing arguments imply a
schema bug, not a user mistake. Emission order follows Docker's grammar:
optional --platform first, then image, then ":tag" or "@digest", then
optional "AS stage", then LF.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Pull five string arguments by position, write FROM-line tokens with
optional fields gated on non-empty length. Matches dockerfile_printer's
emit_from_instruction format byte-for-byte.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_from_call" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, hir_call_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Translate a dockerfile_from(image, tag, digest, stage_name, platform) call.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Validate arity 5, then emit FROM line in canonical Docker grammar order.
    @End Implementation

    Let args_ptr be proc get_call_arguments with hir_call_ptr

    If args_ptr is equal to 0:
        proc set_backend_error with backend_ptr, "FROM call has no arguments"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args_ptr

    If arg_count is not equal to 5:
        proc set_backend_error with backend_ptr, "FROM call requires 5 arguments"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let image_node be proc list_get from List with args_ptr, 0
    Let tag_node be proc list_get from List with args_ptr, 1
    Let digest_node be proc list_get from List with args_ptr, 2
    Let stage_node be proc list_get from List with args_ptr, 3
    Let platform_node be proc list_get from List with args_ptr, 4

    Let image be proc extract_string_literal with image_node
    Let tag be proc extract_string_literal with tag_node
    Let digest be proc extract_string_literal with digest_node
    Let stage_name be proc extract_string_literal with stage_node
    Let platform be proc extract_string_literal with platform_node

    proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "FROM "

    Let platform_len be proc string_length from StringCore with platform
    If platform_len is greater than 0:
        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "--platform="
        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, platform
        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, " "
    End If

    proc emit_text with backend_ptr, image

    Let tag_len be proc string_length from StringCore with tag
    If tag_len is greater than 0:
        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, ":"
        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, tag
    Otherwise:
        Let digest_len be proc string_length from StringCore with digest
        If digest_len is greater than 0:
            proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "@"
            proc emit_text with backend_ptr, digest
        End If
    End If

    Let stage_len be proc string_length from StringCore with stage_name
    If stage_len is greater than 0:
        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, " AS "
        proc emit_text with backend_ptr, stage_name
    End If

    proc emit_newline_byte with backend_ptr
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
RUN shell form is the unquoted "RUN cmd" variant that Docker passes through
/bin/sh -c. The HIR encoding is dockerfile_run_shell(command:String).
Emission writes the command line verbatim — no escaping is applied because
the source token already represents the canonical shell string.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Extract single String argument and emit "RUN " + command + LF.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_run_shell_call" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, hir_call_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Translate a dockerfile_run_shell(command) call to shell-form RUN.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Emit "RUN " + command + newline.
    @End Implementation

    Let args_ptr be proc get_call_arguments with hir_call_ptr

    If args_ptr is equal to 0:
        proc set_backend_error with backend_ptr, "RUN shell call has no arguments"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args_ptr

    If arg_count is not equal to 1:
        proc set_backend_error with backend_ptr, "RUN shell call requires 1 argument"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let command_node be proc list_get from List with args_ptr, 0
    Let command be proc extract_string_literal with command_node

    proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "RUN "
    proc emit_text with backend_ptr, command
    proc emit_newline_byte with backend_ptr
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
RUN exec form bypasses the shell. Encoded as dockerfile_run_exec(args:
Array[String]); each array element becomes a quoted argv token in the
JSON-array Dockerfile syntax.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Extract single Array argument, emit "RUN " + JSON-array + newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_run_exec_call" that takes backend_ptr as Integer, hir_call_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Translate a dockerfile_run_exec(args) call to exec-form RUN.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Emit "RUN " + JSON-array + newline.
    @End Implementation

    Let args_ptr be proc get_call_arguments with hir_call_ptr

    If args_ptr is equal to 0:
        proc set_backend_error with backend_ptr, "RUN exec call has no arguments"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from List with args_ptr

    If arg_count is not equal to 1:
        proc set_backend_error with backend_ptr, "RUN exec call requires 1 argument"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let array_node be proc list_get from List with args_ptr, 0
    Let children_list be proc extract_array_children with array_node

    proc emit_text with backend_ptr, "RUN "
    proc emit_json_array_from_hir with backend_ptr, children_list
    proc emit_newline_byte with backend_ptr
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
CMD shell form is the default container command parsed by /bin/sh -c.
Same encoding shape as translate_run_shell_call but emits "CMD" instead
of "RUN" so Docker stages the layer differently.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Extract single String argument and emit "CMD " + command + LF.
@End Implementation

